segments.text: The interview with Chester Clark, and the question is, did he feel that the media took certain things about the Vietnam conflict out of context in reporting?
I mentioned Lieutenant Calley, who, indeed, if you look at the things that he was accused of doing and then some of the things that he admitted doing, those are things that are appalling to us.
The murders of people, whether innocent people or guilty people or whatever,
The murders of mass people recalled to people's minds the things that happened in Germany with the Jews.
And the Israel was compared to that sometimes.
And I don't know what was in his mind, what he thought about, what he had been through, even if the actions he took were justified or not.
I just know that they were played up so that he was looked upon as a madman and did all these murders because he had the power to.

and his supervisors were were scrutinized for their part in it and not and he was he was uh when he said i was following direct orders since municipal and the whole military was looked at as you give a guy an order and he follows it without thinking about it so the military played up a lot of things that have happened for a long time and just applied them to vietnam
All right, how did you feel about the anti-war demonstrators and the draft dodgers, the people who burned their draft cards or went to Canada, that sort of thing, the anti-war sentiment as a whole?
As a professional military man, of course, I didn't like any of it.
And I felt there would be better ways to show your objection to a war.
And I would never understand someone going to Canada to avoid military service.
there's the demonstrations that they had were very, I was, I was a part of those demonstrations, if you will.
When I came back from Vietnam, my assignment was at the Pentagon and I drove to work along the Potomac on the west side of the Potomac.
There were army tanks on the east side of the Potomac that were around the reflection pool and in front of the Lincoln Memorial where they were having a lot of demonstrations.
So I saw the demonstrations firsthand and
was affected by the demonstrations.
In fact, one of the things that we had briefings on were the demonstrations that were going on in the States and why they were happening and how a certain amount of people felt.
But then on the other hand, you'd receive letters and cards from home that were supporting what you were doing, supporting you.

and from schools a lot of schools have their the whole grade write a letter to dear gi or dear mr joe and those things were very refreshing to get because people were telling their kids that the military was doing a job uh did you know any veterans who came back after vietnam and demonstrated against the war or any officers who
became members of Veterans for Peace or Vietnam Veterans Against the War, any of those groups?
None at all.
I was, and probably the geography of where I was played a part in it.
I was stationed at the Pentagon and then stationed at military bases.
And no one that I was aware of was a member of any group that opposed Vietnam or had any
or join any group that demonstrate actively against what we've done.
So you didn't feel like there was an undercurrent within the military against Vietnam at all?
I didn't.
I really didn't.
The people I was with, we had a job to do.
We realized the importance of the job and just carried out those tasks that we had to do.
And my task was to support the ground troops that were in Vietnam.
Their task was to keep out this spread of communism.
And the way they were doing it was with their way of fighting the war.
And sometimes that was by just simply keeping infiltrators from coming down from the north, by destroying supply lines that were supplying the North Vietnamese and the South.
or by trying to even to help the South Vietnamese to gain their self-respect and be self-reliant.
So that was also part of the plan to make Vietnam, South Vietnam, be self-reliant when we did pull out.
The plan you are referring to is Vietnamization, I believe.
Do you feel, and it has been highly talked about after the Vietnam War,
Do you feel like if that plan had been implemented the right way that it would have worked?
Implement the right way, it's very difficult to say because had it been implemented the right way, there would have been a status quo in Vietnam.
We would not have had the North Vietnamese pulling one way and us pulling another.
For them to be self-reliant would have meant they wouldn't have anybody trying to overtake them because they were not strong enough to stand on their own ever.
We touched on this a little while ago.
How did or do you feel about Jane Fonda and her denouncement of the United States?

That was really hard to take because Jane Fonda and her family, of course, being movie folks, I've enjoyed them in movies quite a bit, and Jane Fonda made some statements that even if they'd been true, it would have hurt very much to hear somebody say them.
And no one likes to hear that they've
that they bombed a hospital or a children's home or something like that.

And the reason that we were privileged to the information about the individuals I spoke of that did bomb the SAM site in Hanoi was that the minute Jane Fonda said that, there was doubts in almost everyone's minds that we had done the right thing.
And doubt creeps in that you have, if you've really killed children, and most of us had children,
That really plays on your mind.
So they immediately made available to us the pictures of the SAM site, the geography around it, and we were assured that there was no...
There were, of course, civilian casualties.
Any time you bombed something, there's going to be civilian casualties or casualties of people around.
But there was nothing like hospitals or children's homes.
And it was just not something that she should have said
And, of course, it didn't matter if it was Jane Fonda.
It could have been anybody saying it, and that had the same effect.
But Jane Fonda was one that you expect her to be backing you.
You expect all the young Jane Fondas and the movie stars to have the appeal to people to back you, that people are looking up to.
And it was disappointing that someone of her stature would say something that was that derogatory.
I have known some Vietnam veterans and some military families that will not go to any Jane Fonda movies or will not rent any of her videotapes for aerobics or any of those things.
Do you have that strong a feeling against Jane Fonda or was it just simply at that time what she said?
It was just what she said and not her.
I didn't like her actions, but as for her herself, I would probably like her.
I have nothing
She has apologized since then, recently, for some of the things that she said and did.

And it would be very interesting to know if her versions, like the hospital and the children's home, if that was actually something that she said, that she was prompted to say, or if she really felt that she had been shown what had been hit and bombed.
I have no idea.
She has apologized for...
What reason?
I don't know.
If she apologized because she's sincerely sorry for it, fine.
If she's trying to sell her newest exercise tape or her newest movie, that'd be another story.
Did you or do you know any POWs who came out of the conflict?
Yes, I had one POW that was a POW for seven years.
His name was Ron Burns, and Ron
I met his family before I met him.
I was stationed at the Pentagon when I came back.

And at the Pentagon, I had occasion to meet several people who were working with the POWs and trying to secure the release of the POWs and to recover the bodies of the killed in action and the missing in action to find out what they were doing.
And when I left the Pentagon, I went to Hanscom Air Force Base near Boston.
And while there, I met a family, two boys and the mother, whose husband was a POW, and knew them very well.
And while we were there, he was released and came back.
And he never really talked about his experiences.
He would always tell you things that would be helpful to the occasion.
If in church he was asked to make a talk, he would tell you about how his faith helped him to get through, how his prayers were helped and how he felt that people praying for him helped.

If he was talking to a scout group, he would tell them how his preparedness for being in Vietnam had helped him and how he would prepare for every day and how he would think about those lessons he had learned and disciplined and
how all of his scout training helped him.
He would apply his experiences to whatever he was talking about.
He never showed a lot of any bitterness or any self-pity or any of those kinds of things that have come out from other individuals that were POWs.
He had a very tragic homecoming as much as after he was released after seven years, after about four months in the States,
his wife was found to have terminal cancer and did die later on.
And he took his seven years of POW, his wife's death, he turned all those things into something positive.
He made a good life for himself without retreating or feeling sorry for himself or expecting anybody to do anything for him over and above what they were doing for anybody else.
So you do feel that a lot of coming home after Vietnam

a lot of the problems that some of the veterans have had, if they had dealt with them head on, that they might have, as this may do, that they might have been able to come through without the traumatic experiences?
Yes, I really do.
And when I say that, you have to understand where I'm coming from.
Colonel Burns, of course, was an officer.
I was an officer.
We had different standards we lived by because of the structure of the military itself.
and we probably were not exposed to as many different

uh situations as enlisted people were are people in different areas of vietnam but i think carl burns probably went through as many traumatic experiences with seven years as pow and with his losing his wife and the way he lost her as anyone and he still did not suffer any of the the horrible consequences that some of the people have had have reported to have recently um i've heard
Earlier you mentioned special forces and some of the different groups of the service.
How did you feel about the Green Berets and special forces and those type people?
Did you have respect for those people or did you feel that they were not in the same league as the Air Force?
I couldn't put a number on the amount of respect.
that I had for those people and the amount of respect and gratitude that the American people owe those people for what they did in Vietnam.
I worked with the Special Forces.
I flew in and out of their camps all the time.
I was assigned to them specifically.
And in particular with the Army, I worked with 101st Airborne.
And the Green Berets and Special Forces fought the war.
The Air Force didn't.
We supplied them, we supported them, but we didn't fight the war.
Many times the Air Force was called upon to do such things as drop bombs from 20,000 feet, which takes very little bravery on anyone's part.
We flew into places that were very small landing strips, very difficult to get into, but that required being a good pilot.
It didn't require any bravery at all or anything special.
On one occasion, we took a mortuary team into a site.
A 123 had crashed into a mountain, and 13 people were on board.
There was communications gear on board.
You couldn't get to the site because it was on the side of a mountain.
So we secured helicopters to go to the site.
And we took a marchery team, a first lieutenant, army first lieutenant, and his team were lowered down from a helicopter onto the site itself.
The site was not secure at all.
It was in VC territory, and they owned the mountain it was on.

When we let the crew down, we let down the lieutenant with his six people, and they were responsible for securing the site as best they could, and in the wreckage itself, find those 13 bodies, put them in body bags, and prepare them for bringing them out of there to take them back to Thompson Nook, to the mortuary.
One of the political...
hang-ups that we had was not a hang-up.
The engineer on the crew was from Thailand.
It was absolutely necessary that we return that individual's body to the Thai government.
And the wreckage itself is very difficult to find anybody's, much less a specific one.
But that lieutenant with his crew went down, and this was part of their everyday mission.
When they got on the ground, the fog came in.

and we had we could not get them out at one time we had to go back to the to our base and wait for the fog to lift go back in and pick them up the lieutenant and his bunch stayed overnight and they've been prepared to go down and come right back up but they stayed overnight they got the bodies they secured the area they found that they had to
To sleep, they had to tie themselves to a tree because it was that steep on the mountainside.
They destroyed some of the classified communications gear that was in the C-123 when it crashed.
We went back the next morning to pick them up.
I consider what they had done very heroic, very deserving of some kind of recognition in the medal.
But their attitude was they'd just simply done their job, and they expected nothing for it but just to go back to their base and start again.
And when we radioed down to the lieutenant, we said, you know, you spent the night, no food, no shelter, no clothing.
He says, anything that you really want.
And he came back over the radio and he says, yes, sir.
He says, I sure would like a chocolate bar.
And that was his concern that he was still kind of, you know, there's nothing like get us out of here, blah, blah, blah.
But we did get them out.
And the airplane was...
The airplane was totally destroyed.
They did destroy the gear that couldn't be left on the ground.
They did find the tie with the symbolic Buddha that they wear.
We did avoid what could have turned out to be an international incident by returning the correct body to Thailand.
And these guys were just doing their job.
They expected nothing from it.
as opposed to other people who expected medals or write-ups for everything they did.
Do you feel that Vietnam, that there were medals handed out that were undeserved in Vietnam more so than any other wars?
Well, there were some handed out that were not deserved, and the reason they were is because of the position individuals were in.
When I was in Saigon as a safety officer,
one ticker individual, was in a position to write up the things for a medal.
And he himself came out very decorated, even though he didn't, he never got out of Saigon.
And he wasn't a regular flyer.
He flew when he had to, to go somewhere and investigate an accident.
But he had a lot of medals.
Some of the medals were a little, I'll have some stories behind them that
that are interesting.
We had, in a C-123, there are cables that run back to the back that control the elevator and the rudder.
And these cables sometimes fray and have little spikes that stick out on them.
When we would take hits, we were usually getting hit in the back of the airplane, and the things the guns they were shooting with were not strong enough to go through the plane.
They would go through the bottom skin of the plane, hit the top of the plane, and stay inside the plane.
You'd hear them rattling around.
And one particular time, we had taken several hits in the back of the plane, and we knew that the slugs were in the plane.
And so my, one of the, no.
It wasn't my crew, but it was a crew.
And the loadmaster went back to the back to find the slug.
And he took out the bulkhead part that allows you to go to the tail of the airplane and reached down to the bottom of the plane to pick up these slugs that were back there.
When he did, he rubbed his hand across the cable and cut himself.
And a cut in Vietnam is not like a cut anywhere else.
Nothing gets well by itself.
You must doctor it.
If you leave it alone, it would
be infected just quickly.
So he went to the doctor.
As they landed, this thing did bother him.
So he went into the hospital.
And they were cleaning it out and working on it.
And someone said, how did you get this?
And he said, well, I was taking a shell out of the back of the plane.
And they wrote this up on their hospital notes.
And later on, someone read it and says, oh, well, here's the guy that was wounded by a shell in a plane.
He deserves a Purple Heart.
And it turns out that this was someone put him in for the Purple Heart.
And he had already left Vietnam.
He was back in the States.
So the paperwork came back down to me, a safety officer, to find this guy's unit to confirm he deserved a Purple Heart and to present him with this Purple Heart.
And when the guy was contacted, of course, the true story came out that he had been scratched with the cable and not been shot.
But that was just one of those things that someone had written up because more than not,
Individuals who deserved awards weren't looking for them, like the mortuary team.
They were not looking for awards.
And when I flew people around, one particular flight in the C-123, there were no seats.
We set the people on pallets, eight or 10 across, and put a big strap over them.
And your briefing to them was, if we crash, just bend forward and hope for the best, because there's no safety constraint.

And you would look to the back before you'd take off, and I remember one particular flight, I looked around to the back, and there was a kid sitting there with his M-16 on one shoulder, reading a comic book, and out of his pocket was sticking a purple heart that he had received, and just sticking out of his pocket.
Well, most people would have them waving them and say, look what I've got.
He took it just for granted that he had this thing there.
And there he was, reading a comic book, being flown right back into a combat zone.
What are the Vietnam movies that you've seen, and which one do you consider to be closest to the real Vietnam experience, or what you were involved in?

Well, unfortunately I haven't seen that many movies, but of course I've seen The Green Berets, and it did have some very authentic parts to it, but it had a lot of Hollywood commercialism in it also that were not true.
I did see The Good Morning Vietnam.

And aside from being very funny, that did have a few scenes in it where it was very true that an individual like the one that was the North Vietnamese that got him out of the cafe before it was bombed, those things did happen.
people were aware that things were going to happen before they happened.
And when I first arrived at Saigon, we were one day at the base.
Someone said, I wouldn't hang around the base too long today.
I'd go on home right after, you know, right after when you finish going home.
I said, why?
He says, well, look.
And you could see that no Vietnamese were hanging around the base.
They were all leaving early.
And at that time,
There was a search of the Vietnamese as they walked out the gate.
And the two main things they were searching for were silverware and the soap, the washing powders.
They would steal that frequently.
But they would have a little tub there that would take the silverware off of them, spoons and knives and forks.
But when they all left, quickly, they knew something was going to happen.
And sure enough, that night,
the base was mortared because they were all just filing out leaving.
So they were aware of what was happening.
I know you mentioned earlier that you have seen the USO and that you did move some of the equipment.
It was highly classified.
Do you believe that the USO helped to bring the morale of the troops up?
Or do you believe it was beneficial to the troops?
Oh, I really believe it helped.
Very beneficial.
And the most memorable occasion I had was at the USO show with Bob Hope and Barbara McNair sang Silent Night.
And there were approximately 4,500 people in the audience that night.
That was the quietest that you could ever hear a hillside.
And that brought home to people more than anything else.
This was a show that had the Miss America, Raquel Welch, and all the trimmings.
But the thing I remember the most is Barbara McNair.
You just echo through that.
And that just brought Christmas home just like it was right there.
Then the other show that was there that was just super was Martha Rae.
She performed Hello Dolly, which brought you back to the States quite a bit.
But then she came out, decked out in Green Beret outfit, the whole thing, and just talked.
And you could identify.
Everybody identified with what she was saying.
Everybody identified with her.
And she made a very strong point of telling you,
how much she supported you, what she was for, that she represented the majority of the people in the United States, that you were not over here in vain, that you hadn't been forgotten.
And you went away with such a good feeling that her show was just fantastic.
Did it help to relieve some of the media problems that had been...

reported about vietnam did that help to to make you realize that the majority was behind you at that point yes and it was very it was much easier to believe her than you know it was just really to believe what she was saying it helped to reiterate why you were there yeah yeah she when she said you're doing a good job we believe in you you know that that meant everything in the world to us have you kept in contact with your unit or with your crew members since you've left vietnam
I haven't.
And after I came back from Vietnam, I was at the Pentagon.
And I did go to a Friday classified briefing every Friday to maintain contact with the unit and see what they were doing.

But as time went along, I got very busy with what I was doing, very involved with my current job, and got completely away from what was happening in Vietnam and simply followed it through the news media like every other person in the United States.
Did you have trouble readjusting when you came back to the weather or to your family, to not being in a war situation?
I would like to say no, I had no trouble at all.
I probably did and don't realize what it was.
One of the, when I got off the plane, well actually,
The first time I got back, weather was a problem.
I was in a very thin raincoat, and we landed in Seattle, Washington.
And Lord, I don't know how cold it was, but that raincoat wasn't enough.
But when I got off the plane to Dallas and came out, I was one of the last ones out of the plane.
And when I walked out, there was this little three-year-old kid that kept saying, Daddy, Daddy, Daddy, everybody in uniform.
And it was Tom, and he didn't know.
He just knew Daddy was in uniform and was coming out.
And probably I had trouble adjusting to them as they did to me.
But it's like anything else.
I remember only the good and not the bad.
Very true.
Very true.
What are you doing now?
And do you feel that your experience in Vietnam has helped you in the rest of your life and in coping with things?
My current job now is I teach high school.
I actually work in high school.
And my military career overall has helped me in being a teacher, as much as in Vietnam as well as in my job in the Air Force.
I was always an instructor pilot or an instructor for ground school, far flying.
And in that capacity, I learned the teaching techniques.
I worked with people.
And I've just taken those skills and, of course, using my math background, I now teach math in high school.
And the only thing I find that is lacking is I can't order the kids around like I could the people under me in the Air Force.
Not quite as captive.
No.

But I have used all of my experience in coping with different situations, especially different situations in Vietnam, to cope with situations in the States which do not ever approach the severity of the situation I was in.
My final question is,
Do you feel that serving in Vietnam changed you, and if so, how?
I really don't think it changed me in any way that I wouldn't have changed ordinarily, except it did it faster.
In other words, if you're going to grow up, some people grow up
at a certain rate of speed.
I was going at that certain rate of speed.
I was doing things that you do.
I came out of high school and went to college.
I came out of college and went in the military.
I stayed in the military and things were just happening for me as they should happen.
I got married, I had children.
I went to Vietnam
and probably matured four for one.
I probably came back more mature, more aware of people's problems, more aware that there were more problems in the world than taking the trash out to the curb on a Friday morning.
That helped me to grow up faster.
be more tolerant of other people's problems and to learn to live with situations that are out of the ordinary.
Learn to go from a very comfortable home in the States to a situation in Vietnam where suddenly there was, the first time I saw my uniforms washed
on a rock, with a rock hitting him on the floor.
That, I thought, you think about how far away that is from a, from a washing machine back home.
And at the time,
It was very easy to compare, and when I got back from Vietnam, it was very easy to look at the things that we had that we take for granted every day and realize how lucky we are and how much we have.
And to also realize that this idealism that we had, that we could keep communism out of Vietnam,
was really worthwhile, that we really were fighting for something worthwhile.
And the way that Saigon is now Ho Chi Minh City, that the South Vietnamese are now under communist rule, tells me that we were doing the right thing.
We were doing it for the right cause.
I just wish that we could have accomplished what we set out to do.
Thank you very much.
I appreciate your time.
